threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit LSB executable, MIPS, MIPS-I version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, no section header

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This ELF binary is a highly functional IoT botnet agent, specifically a variant of the Gafgyt (Qbot) family targeting MIPS-based devices. The malware establishes persistence via multiple methods, including crontab modification (sub_4074ec), inittab respawn injection (sub_40763c), and rc.local script updates (sub_407804). It features a full suite of DDoS attack modules including SYN floods (labeled as 'PAN'), UDP, HTTP, and 'STD' floods (sub_40ac18, sub_40b118, sub_40a320). C2 communication is IRC-based, utilizing a main loop (sub_408df8) to handle commands like reverse shells ('CBACK' in sub_4061fc), file downloads, and SSH scanning. Anti-analysis features include process checks for 'strace' and 'tcpdump' (sub_408d48), while anti-forensics measures redirect bash history to /dev/null. The binary also fingerprints IoT devices by reading NVRAM and model information (sub_40bb50) and actively eliminates competing bots by scanning /proc/net/tcp to find and kill processes owning specific network sockets (sub_40cb8c).
